---
import DocsLayout from '../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import { Code } from 'astro:components';

const installSource = `force-app/bedrock/lib`;

const installConsole = `force-app/bedrock/console-app`;

const sections = [
  { label: 'Start Small', href: '#start-small' },
  { label: 'First Three Tools', href: '#first-three-tools' },
  { label: 'Move Work Safely', href: '#move-work-safely' },
  { label: 'Operational Visibility', href: '#operational-visibility' },
  { label: 'Validation', href: '#validation' }
];
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Getting Started | sf-bedrock docs"
  description="Start building with sf-bedrock by adopting the testing foundation first, then adding async and scheduler patterns where they solve real platform problems."
  eyebrow="Start"
  sections={sections}
>
  <Fragment slot="header">
    <h1>Start with the seams your tests need.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Bedrock works best when it disappears into ordinary Apex. Add the small
      pieces first, prove the pattern in tests, then bring in the heavier tools
      when volume or operations demand them.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <section class="doc-section" id="start-small">
    <h2>Start Small</h2>
    <p>
      The framework source lives here:
    </p>
    <Code code={installSource} lang="text" />
    <p>
      You do not need to adopt every library at once. Most teams start by routing
      service-layer reads and writes through <code>Query</code> and
      <code>DML</code>, then use <code>TestData</code> to build realistic records
      without setup bloat.
    </p>
    <div class="callout">
      <strong>The goal is boring production code</strong>
      <p>
        Bedrock should make the safe path easy. Your services should still read
        like normal Apex, and your tests should prove behavior without begging the
        database for help.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="first-three-tools">
    <h2>First Three Tools</h2>
    <div class="doc-grid">
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3><a href="/test-data">TestData</a></h3>
        <p>
          Build in-memory records with mock Ids, parent relationships, and fields
          the normal constructor will not let you set.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3><a href="/dml">DML</a></h3>
        <p>
          Replace raw writes with a tiny facade. Production commits. Tests capture
          inserts, updates, upserts, deletes, and undeletes.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3><a href="/query">Query</a></h3>
        <p>
          Keep SOQL in production and swap in test results without relying on org
          data, <code>SeeAllData</code>, or fragile setup.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3><a href="/platform-cache">PlatformCache</a></h3>
        <p>
          Put org and session cache behind a mockable seam when cache-backed code
          needs real assertions.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="move-work-safely">
    <h2>Move Work Safely</h2>
    <p>
      Once your service layer has clean seams, use the automation tools where the
      platform starts pushing back.
    </p>
    <ul class="token-list">
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/trigger-handler">TriggerHandler</a></strong>
        <span>Keep triggers thin and route context to the hook that owns the work.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/record-buffer">RecordBuffer</a></strong>
        <span>Stage related writes during a transaction, then flush grouped DML once.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/async">Async</a></strong>
        <span>Process record Ids in tracked background batches instead of burning Queueable slots.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/scheduler">Scheduler</a></strong>
        <span>Run recurring jobs from metadata without consuming one scheduled Apex slot per logical job.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="operational-visibility">
    <h2>Operational Visibility</h2>
    <p>
      The optional Bedrock Console lives here:
    </p>
    <Code code={installConsole} lang="text" />
    <p>
      It gives teams views for async backlog, errors, completed work, async job
      configuration, and scheduler status. It is there for debugging and recovery;
      the programming model still lives in the library contracts.
    </p>
    <p>
      Read the short <a href="/console">Bedrock Console</a> page when you are
      ready to give admins and developers an operations window.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="validation">
    <h2>Validation</h2>
    <p>
      Deploy the library source you use, then run the smallest tests that prove
      the behavior you changed. For new code, prefer focused tests that assert
      mutations, DML calls, query results, or async work records.
    </p>
    <p>
      Keep the first adoption boring: one service, one test, one clear win. Then
      repeat.
    </p>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
